   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="transcription">
            <p>
<lb corresp="#a1x"/><w>ñakciya</w>
<lb corresp="#a2x"/><w>lä<add>ktsetse</add></w>
<lb corresp="#b1x"/><w>rätrona</w>
<lb corresp="#b2x"/><w>kseññeṣṣe</w></p>
         </div>
         <div type="translation">
            <p><choice corresp="#a1x"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">divine</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a2x"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">brilliant(?)</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b1x"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">red</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b2x"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">belonging to nirvāṇa</seg></seg></choice></p>
         </div>
         <div type="comments">
            <p><note type="remarks">“T III S 51” only to be found on tag/label.</note><note corresp="#a1x" type="lingcomment">Note the spelling <hi>ña</hi> for regular <hi>ñä</hi> in the first syllable.</note><note corresp="#a1x" type="philcomment">glosses Skt. <hi>[v]y·</hi>, which can be restored as <hi>(di)vy·</hi> 'divine' on the basis of the gloss (perhaps <hi>(di)vy(ā)</hi>, since <hi>ñakciya</hi> is nom.sg.fem.).</note><note corresp="#a2x" type="philcomment">Under this line, the first akṣara of a further, so far undeciphered gloss is found: TB(?) <hi>[w]ä</hi> under Skt. <hi>sarvabhā [t]·</hi> 'shining in all directions (?)' (<bibl><title corresp="ref:wille2012"/><citedRange>26</citedRange></bibl>) reads <hi>sarvabh[ā] –</hi>). If the reading is in fact <hi>[<hi rend="underline">l</hi>]ä</hi>, the gloss may have been <hi>lä(ktsetse)</hi> v.s. (for class. <hi>läk<hi rend="subscript">u</hi>tsetse</hi>) 'brilliant'.</note><note corresp="#b1x" type="lingcomment"><hi>rätrona</hi> 'red' is a pl.fem.</note><note corresp="#b2x" type="lingcomment">Note that <hi>kseññe°</hi> is a late form for <hi>kselñe</hi> 'nirvāṇa' (<bibl><title corresp="ref:peyrot2008"/><citedRange>64</citedRange></bibl>).</note><note corresp="#b2x" type="philcomment">glosses Skt. <hi>niḥśreya[s](a)</hi> 'most ecellent; ultimate bliss'. Over this line a further gloss is found: <ref type="ms" target="#b1x"/> TB <hi><hi rend="underline">ra</hi>trona</hi> 'red', but unfortunately the Sanskrit line to which this gloss belonged is not preserved.</note></p>
         </div>
         <div type="bibliography">
            <p><label>other</label><bibl><title corresp="ref:peyrot2014"/><citedRange>161</citedRange></bibl>; <bibl><title corresp="ref:wille2012"/><citedRange>26</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
            <p><label>Online access</label><bibl><title corresp="ref:idp0000"/><ref target="http://idp.bbaw.de/database/oo_loader.a4d?pm=SHT 4413 " type="external">SHT 4413</ref></bibl></p>
         </div>
